{"title": "Any deal between Intesa, Generali would need many authorizations: BOI", "text": "FILE PHOTO: A banner with a logo of Generali insurance is seen outside one of its branch offices in Telfs, Austria, November 1, 2016. REUTERS/Leonhard Foeger/File Photo\n\nFILE PHOTO: An Intesa Sanpaolo Bank logo is seen in Milan, Italy, October 1, 2013. REUTERS/Stefano Rellandini/File Photo\n\nMODENA, Italy A possible tie-up between Italy's top retail bank Intesa Sanpaolo (ISP.MI) and insurer Generali (GASI.MI) would need \"many authorizations\" from regulators, a top official at the Bank of Italy said on Saturday.\n\nSalvatore Rossi, who is the central bank's director-general and also heads insurance watchdog Ivass, said both institutions were closely monitoring the situation and had contacted the two groups.\n\nIntesa said this week it was examining a possible deal with Generali.\n\n(Reporting by Luca Trogni, writing by Silvia Aloisi; editing by Philip Pullella)", "keywords": ["sanpaolo", "authorizations", "deal", "italy", "possible", "writing", "seen", "boi", "logo", "need", "generali", "intesa", "insurance", "bank"], "epoch": "1485627834", "authors": ["Reuters Editorial"], "date": "20170128"}